http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Debate II is a two-semester course that will provide students with an intermediate understanding of the dynamics of argumentation and effective communication. Debate II is designed to help students master preparation skills and develop an understanding of debate procedures at an intermediate level. Students in Debate II will express ideas and present information in a variety of formal presentations and debate formats. Students will demonstrate appropriate verbal and nonverbal communication while using ethical debating practices. Students will engage in indepth, topic-specific research from informational texts.
Tools
Students will utilize the necessary tools for debate at an intermediate level.
Examine ethical dilemmas

Apply critical thinking skills:
  • logical fallacies
  • source validity

Refine presentation skills:
  • audience adaptation
  • reduce vocal fillers
  • strengthen voice
Employ debate terminology

Employ persuasive techniques:
  • ethos
  • logos
  • pathos
Complete specialized debate flow sheets
Utilize the steps of refutation
Incorporate current and political events in case specific arguments
Implement basic rules of evidence
Preparation
Students will master preparation skills needed to debate at an intermediate level.

Synthesize information from a variety of sources:
  • agency resources
  • cross-curricular collaboration
  • exhaustive, topic-specific research
  • historical texts that influence current policy (e.g., foundational texts, major philosophers)
Analyze economic factors that influence current issues

Construct topic-specific cases and briefs:
  • disadvantages
  • impact turns
  • solvency turns
Collaborate with others to define issues and develop strategies
Challenge the status quo and current policy proposals using a variety of arguments and rhetorical devices
Use formal register
Procedures
Students will follow proper debate procedures.
Broaden complex arguments

Conduct strategic cross examination:
  • entrapment
  • leading questions
  • self-generated questions
Participate in debates beyond the classroom setting
